1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,720
No lawyer.

2
00:00:01,020 --> 00:00:02,020
A borrowed pencil.

3
00:00:02,620 --> 00:00:03,613
One prisoner —

4
00:00:03,940 --> 00:00:05,400
about to beat the Supreme Court.

5
00:00:05,980 --> 00:00:07,000
Nine to nothing.

6
00:00:07,780 --> 00:00:10,860
In 1963, almost no one in America had

7
00:00:10,860 --> 00:00:13,180
heard the name Clarence Earl Gideon.

8
00:00:13,960 --> 00:00:16,380
He was a drifter, in and out of

9
00:00:16,380 --> 00:00:19,200
trouble his whole life, sitting in a Florida

10
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:21,680
cell for a crime he swore he did

11
00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:22,320
not commit.

12
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:25,340
He had stood in a courtroom and asked

13
00:00:25,340 --> 00:00:29,384
the judge for one simple thing —

14
00:00:29,385 --> 00:00:29,885
a lawyer.

15
00:00:29,886 --> 00:00:29,940
The judge said no.

16
00:00:30,620 --> 00:00:33,740
And that single word, "no," is where this

17
00:00:33,740 --> 00:00:35,320
story actually begins.

18
00:00:36,360 --> 00:00:38,120
Here is something most of us assume is

19
00:00:38,120 --> 00:00:40,980
just permanently true: that if you are

20
00:00:40,980 --> 00:00:43,040
arrested and cannot afford a lawyer,

21
00:00:43,440 --> 00:00:44,900
the court has to give you one.

22
00:00:45,560 --> 00:00:47,520
We treat it like a feature built into

23
00:00:47,520 --> 00:00:48,720
America from the start.

24
00:00:49,160 --> 00:00:50,040
It was not.

25
00:00:50,760 --> 00:00:52,580
For most of this country's history,

26
00:00:53,020 --> 00:00:54,860
if you were too poor to hire a

27
00:00:54,860 --> 00:00:57,500
lawyer, you could be put on trial alone

28
00:01:02,030 --> 00:01:02,330
—

29
00:01:02,331 --> 00:01:02,831
one frightened person against a trained

30
00:01:02,832 --> 00:01:03,820
prosecutor whose entire job was to convict

31
00:01:03,820 --> 00:01:04,340
you.

32
00:01:05,120 --> 00:01:07,360
The guarantee of a free lawyer is younger

33
00:01:07,360 --> 00:01:08,320
than your grandparents.

34
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:11,680
And it exists because of one stubborn

35
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:15,180
prisoner, one handwritten letter, and one

36
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:18,040
unanimous decision in 1963.

37
00:01:19,220 --> 00:01:21,760
Over the next twelve minutes: how a man

38
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:24,760
nobody believed in forced the Supreme Court

39
00:01:24,760 --> 00:01:27,420
to rewrite the rules of every criminal trial

40
00:01:27,420 --> 00:01:29,164
in America —

41
00:01:29,165 --> 00:01:31,160
and the imperfect system that ruling left

42
00:01:31,160 --> 00:01:31,760
behind.

43
00:01:32,460 --> 00:01:34,100
Start in a Florida courtroom,

44
00:01:34,460 --> 00:01:35,440
1961.

45
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:38,860
Clarence Earl Gideon is charged with

46
00:01:38,860 --> 00:01:41,560
breaking into a poolroom and stealing a

47
00:01:41,560 --> 00:01:43,085
little money and some bottles of drink —

48
00:01:44,060 --> 00:01:46,240
under Florida law, a felony.

49
00:01:46,860 --> 00:01:47,800
He is poor.

50
00:01:48,380 --> 00:01:50,540
He has been in and out of prison

51
00:01:50,540 --> 00:01:51,100
before.

52
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:53,600
And he knows, the way you know a

53
00:01:53,600 --> 00:01:55,560
thing in your gut, that he cannot do

54
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:56,140
this alone.

55
00:01:57,060 --> 00:01:59,120
So he asks the court to appoint a

56
00:01:59,120 --> 00:01:59,900
lawyer for him.

57
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:02,460
The judge tells him the law does not

58
00:02:02,460 --> 00:02:04,983
allow it —

59
00:02:04,984 --> 00:02:05,460
in Florida at that time,

60
00:02:05,860 --> 00:02:08,540
a free lawyer was provided only when a

61
00:02:08,540 --> 00:02:10,200
person's life was on the line,

62
00:02:10,700 --> 00:02:12,420
in a death-penalty case.

63
00:02:13,420 --> 00:02:15,180
Gideon's case is not one of those.

64
00:02:15,740 --> 00:02:18,140
The chair where his lawyer should sit stays

65
00:02:18,140 --> 00:02:18,600
empty.

66
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:21,420
Picture what a trial actually is.

67
00:02:21,780 --> 00:02:24,781
It is a contest with rules —

68
00:02:25,220 --> 00:02:27,440
rules about what evidence can come in,

69
00:02:27,960 --> 00:02:29,780
which questions can be asked,

70
00:02:30,140 --> 00:02:31,980
what a jury is allowed to hear.

71
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:35,820
On one side stands a prosecutor who has

72
00:02:35,820 --> 00:02:37,520
done this hundreds of times,

73
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:40,000
who knows every one of those rules by

74
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:40,320
heart.

75
00:02:41,120 --> 00:02:42,440
On the other side, now,

76
00:02:42,440 --> 00:02:46,260
stands Gideon: no training, no preparation,

77
00:02:47,140 --> 00:02:49,660
trying to defend his own freedom in a

78
00:02:49,660 --> 00:02:51,060
language he does not speak.

79
00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:52,720
He does his best.

80
00:02:53,300 --> 00:02:54,920
He makes an opening statement,

81
00:02:55,420 --> 00:02:58,280
he questions witnesses, he argues to the

82
00:02:58,280 --> 00:02:58,560
jury.

83
00:02:59,340 --> 00:03:01,360
But doing your best is not the same

84
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:02,780
as knowing what you are doing.

85
00:03:03,420 --> 00:03:05,080
The verdict comes back guilty,

86
00:03:05,080 --> 00:03:07,360
and the court sends him to prison for

87
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:08,060
five years.

88
00:03:08,840 --> 00:03:11,100
For almost anyone else, that is the end.

89
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:14,120
A poor man, convicted, locked away,

90
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:14,860
out of moves.

91
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:17,880
But Gideon has one move left that no

92
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:19,421
one expects —

93
00:03:19,422 --> 00:03:20,640
and it costs five cents.

94
00:03:21,580 --> 00:03:23,780
In his cell, Gideon does something quietly

95
00:03:23,780 --> 00:03:24,540
extraordinary.

96
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:27,140
He gets hold of a pencil and some

97
00:03:27,140 --> 00:03:29,340
prison paper, and in careful,

98
00:03:29,340 --> 00:03:32,240
hand-printed letters he writes directly to

99
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:35,346
the Supreme Court of the United States —

100
00:03:35,347 --> 00:03:37,000
asking them to hear his case.

101
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:39,680
He cannot pay the court's fees,

102
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:42,240
so he files as what the law calls

103
00:03:42,240 --> 00:03:44,888
a pauper —

104
00:03:44,889 --> 00:03:45,400
a person too poor to pay.

105
00:03:46,500 --> 00:03:47,840
No firm is behind him.

106
00:03:48,260 --> 00:03:50,400
No famous attorney is making calls.

107
00:03:51,120 --> 00:03:52,740
It is just one prisoner,

108
00:03:52,740 --> 00:03:56,712
arguing that what happened to him —

109
00:03:56,713 --> 00:03:59,159
being tried without a lawyer —

110
00:03:59,160 --> 00:04:00,660
was not just unlucky, but unconstitutional.

111
00:04:01,780 --> 00:04:03,840
And here is the wall standing directly in

112
00:04:03,840 --> 00:04:04,340
his way.

113
00:04:05,220 --> 00:04:08,140
Twenty years earlier, in a case called Betts

114
00:04:08,140 --> 00:04:08,300
v.

115
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:11,560
Brady, the Supreme Court had already looked

116
00:04:11,560 --> 00:04:14,753
at almost this exact question —

117
00:04:14,754 --> 00:04:15,860
and had ruled the other way.

118
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:18,600
Betts said that states did not have to

119
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:20,860
hand every poor defendant a lawyer.

120
00:04:21,580 --> 00:04:24,400
A free lawyer was required only in "special

121
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:26,842
circumstances" —

122
00:04:26,843 --> 00:04:27,500
if you were very young,

123
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:30,520
or could not read, or the case was

124
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:31,800
unusually complex.

125
00:04:32,780 --> 00:04:36,160
An ordinary poor man, in an ordinary case,

126
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:38,360
was expected to manage on his own.

127
00:04:39,100 --> 00:04:41,600
So Gideon is not just asking the Court

128
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:42,320
to help him.

129
00:04:42,880 --> 00:04:45,220
He is asking the most powerful court in

130
00:04:45,220 --> 00:04:47,220
the country to admit it had been wrong

131
00:04:49,249 --> 00:04:49,549
—

132
00:04:49,550 --> 00:04:51,360
to overturn its own decision and rewrite the

133
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:52,960
rule for every state at once.

134
00:04:53,860 --> 00:04:56,120
Prisoners send the Supreme Court thousands

135
00:04:56,120 --> 00:04:58,680
of these handwritten petitions every year.

136
00:04:59,240 --> 00:05:01,660
The Court turns away almost all of them.

137
00:05:02,140 --> 00:05:04,080
It did not turn away Gideon's.

138
00:05:04,480 --> 00:05:07,456
The justices agreed to hear the case —

139
00:05:07,457 --> 00:05:09,460
and then did something that turns the whole

140
00:05:09,460 --> 00:05:10,460
story on its head.

141
00:05:11,380 --> 00:05:13,020
The man who had been denied a lawyer

142
00:05:13,020 --> 00:05:15,580
in Florida was now given one of the

143
00:05:15,580 --> 00:05:18,180
finest lawyers in America: the Court

144
00:05:18,180 --> 00:05:20,560
appointed a top Washington attorney named

145
00:05:20,560 --> 00:05:23,073
Abe Fortas —

146
00:05:23,074 --> 00:05:25,616
a future Supreme Court justice himself —

147
00:05:25,617 --> 00:05:26,420
to argue Gideon's side.

148
00:05:27,260 --> 00:05:29,720
The question was no longer just about one

149
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:30,800
man in one cell.

150
00:05:31,460 --> 00:05:33,820
It had become a question about every poor

151
00:05:33,820 --> 00:05:35,200
defendant in the country.

152
00:05:35,940 --> 00:05:38,700
Did the Constitution promise them a lawyer,

153
00:05:38,700 --> 00:05:39,820
or didn't it?

154
00:05:40,480 --> 00:05:43,560
On March 18, 1963, the Supreme Court

155
00:05:43,560 --> 00:05:44,543
answered —

156
00:05:44,940 --> 00:05:46,720
and this time the answer was not close.

157
00:05:47,540 --> 00:05:49,080
The decision was unanimous.

158
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:51,120
Every single justice agreed.

159
00:05:52,440 --> 00:05:54,460
Justice Hugo Black, writing for the Court,

160
00:05:54,460 --> 00:05:55,660
delivered the ruling.

161
00:05:56,400 --> 00:05:58,920
The reasoning was almost startlingly plain.

162
00:05:59,580 --> 00:06:02,480
The Sixth Amendment promises anyone accused

163
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:05,344
of a crime "the assistance of counsel" —

164
00:06:06,760 --> 00:06:08,000
the help of a lawyer.

165
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:11,220
The Court said that promise is not a

166
00:06:11,220 --> 00:06:12,760
luxury or a formality.

167
00:06:13,500 --> 00:06:16,200
In our system, where the government hires

168
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:18,740
trained prosecutors and builds courthouses

169
00:06:18,740 --> 00:06:20,360
and writes the rules of evidence,

170
00:06:21,140 --> 00:06:22,740
a lawyer is not a frill.

171
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:26,155
A lawyer is a necessity —

172
00:06:26,156 --> 00:06:29,140
without one, the trial itself is not truly

173
00:06:29,140 --> 00:06:29,560
fair.

174
00:06:30,200 --> 00:06:32,680
And because a fair trial is a basic

175
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:35,880
right, the Court held, that right cannot

176
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:37,960
stop at the federal courthouse door.

177
00:06:38,980 --> 00:06:41,160
Through the Fourteenth Amendment, it binds

178
00:06:41,160 --> 00:06:42,080
the states too.

179
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,480
From that day forward, any state putting a

180
00:06:45,480 --> 00:06:48,040
poor person on trial for a serious crime

181
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:50,684
had to give that person a lawyer —

182
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:52,880
and if they could not afford one,

183
00:06:53,380 --> 00:06:54,920
the state had to provide one.

184
00:06:55,660 --> 00:06:56,900
To say all of this,

185
00:06:56,900 --> 00:06:59,140
the Court had to do the thing Gideon

186
00:06:59,140 --> 00:07:00,540
had dared to ask for.

187
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,160
It reached back and overruled its own

188
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:03,720
precedent.

189
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:05,060
Betts v.

190
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:06,746
Brady —

191
00:07:06,747 --> 00:07:07,838
the wall —

192
00:07:07,839 --> 00:07:08,339
was knocked down.

193
00:07:08,340 --> 00:07:11,120
The old "special circumstances" test was

194
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:11,500
gone.

195
00:07:12,260 --> 00:07:14,420
The new rule was simple enough for anyone

196
00:07:14,420 --> 00:07:17,160
to understand: if you are too poor to

197
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:19,840
hire a lawyer, the state must appoint one

198
00:07:19,840 --> 00:07:20,360
for you.

199
00:07:21,040 --> 00:07:23,440
A handwritten letter from a prison cell had

200
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:25,560
just rewritten the law for the entire

201
00:07:25,560 --> 00:07:26,100
country.

202
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:28,740
But it had not yet done the one

203
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:30,600
thing Gideon cared about most.

204
00:07:31,240 --> 00:07:33,400
Because winning at the Supreme Court did not

205
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:34,460
set Gideon free.

206
00:07:35,180 --> 00:07:38,160
It did something narrower: it threw out his

207
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:41,120
conviction and sent him back to Florida for

208
00:07:41,120 --> 00:07:42,140
a brand-new trial.

209
00:07:42,860 --> 00:07:43,920
The same charges.

210
00:07:44,740 --> 00:07:45,580
The same town.

211
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:49,060
But this time, the empty chair was filled.

212
00:07:50,140 --> 00:07:52,880
Gideon walked into that second trial with an

213
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:54,620
appointed lawyer beside him.

214
00:07:55,420 --> 00:07:57,140
And the difference was night and day.

215
00:07:57,880 --> 00:07:59,920
A real defense attorney picked the case

216
00:07:59,920 --> 00:08:01,569
apart —

217
00:08:01,570 --> 00:08:04,240
testing the witnesses, poking at the state's

218
00:08:04,240 --> 00:08:07,540
story, doing all the things Gideon had never

219
00:08:07,540 --> 00:08:08,660
known how to do alone.

220
00:08:09,340 --> 00:08:11,360
This time, the jury came back with a

221
00:08:11,360 --> 00:08:13,320
different word: not guilty.

222
00:08:14,060 --> 00:08:16,320
Sit with that contrast for a second.

223
00:08:16,960 --> 00:08:19,660
The very same man, facing the very same

224
00:08:19,660 --> 00:08:20,280
accusation.

225
00:08:21,120 --> 00:08:23,520
Alone, he was convicted and sent to prison.

226
00:08:24,240 --> 00:08:26,960
With a lawyer, he was acquitted and walked

227
00:08:26,960 --> 00:08:27,660
out free.

228
00:08:28,660 --> 00:08:30,440
Nothing about Gideon had changed.

229
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:33,080
The only thing that changed was whether

230
00:08:33,080 --> 00:08:35,340
anyone in that room was standing on his

231
00:08:35,340 --> 00:08:35,800
side.

232
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:37,510
That gap —

233
00:08:37,511 --> 00:08:40,640
between facing the state alone and facing it

234
00:08:40,640 --> 00:08:41,933
with help —

235
00:08:41,934 --> 00:08:44,100
is the entire reason the right exists.

236
00:08:44,860 --> 00:08:47,020
And Gideon's win did not stay with Gideon.

237
00:08:47,580 --> 00:08:50,020
His name became the key that unlocked the

238
00:08:50,020 --> 00:08:52,260
same right for everyone behind him.

239
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:55,380
Across the country, states had to build

240
00:08:55,380 --> 00:08:57,360
something new to keep the promise the Court

241
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:00,600
had just made: offices full of lawyers whose

242
00:09:00,600 --> 00:09:03,040
job is to defend people who cannot pay

243
00:09:04,341 --> 00:09:04,641
—

244
00:09:04,642 --> 00:09:04,840
the public defenders.

245
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:07,900
If you have ever heard the phrase "a

246
00:09:07,900 --> 00:09:10,020
public defender will be assigned to you,"

247
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:13,000
that system traces back, in large part,

248
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:14,560
to a prisoner's pencil.

249
00:09:15,220 --> 00:09:17,420
But this is where the hidden room opens

250
00:09:18,471 --> 00:09:18,771
—

251
00:09:18,772 --> 00:09:20,040
and it is not a tidy victory.

252
00:09:20,940 --> 00:09:23,060
The Court could create the right with a

253
00:09:23,060 --> 00:09:24,100
stroke of the pen.

254
00:09:24,880 --> 00:09:26,800
It could not, with that same pen,

255
00:09:27,180 --> 00:09:27,820
pay for it.

256
00:09:28,620 --> 00:09:30,600
A right to a lawyer is only as

257
00:09:30,600 --> 00:09:32,680
real as the lawyer you actually get.

258
00:09:33,340 --> 00:09:34,960
And in the decades since,

259
00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:39,581
public defenders have often been buried —

260
00:09:39,582 --> 00:09:40,280
too many clients, too little money,

261
00:09:40,720 --> 00:09:42,300
too little time for each case.

262
00:09:42,860 --> 00:09:45,100
The promise is guaranteed on paper.

263
00:09:45,820 --> 00:09:47,140
Whether it is fully kept,

264
00:09:47,360 --> 00:09:50,860
case by case, still depends on resources no

265
00:09:50,860 --> 00:09:52,700
court can simply order into being.

266
00:09:53,440 --> 00:09:55,680
So Gideon answered the question Miranda

267
00:09:55,680 --> 00:09:57,260
would raise three years later.

268
00:09:58,020 --> 00:09:59,420
When a suspect is told,

269
00:10:00,140 --> 00:10:01,640
"if you cannot afford a lawyer,

270
00:10:02,120 --> 00:10:04,760
one will be appointed for you," those words

271
00:10:04,760 --> 00:10:05,700
are not a courtesy.

272
00:10:06,340 --> 00:10:08,357
They are a promise —

273
00:10:08,358 --> 00:10:09,520
and it is Gideon's promise.

274
00:10:10,120 --> 00:10:12,860
Step back, and the shape of it is

275
00:10:12,860 --> 00:10:14,040
almost hard to believe.

276
00:10:14,980 --> 00:10:16,540
We did not get the right to a

277
00:10:16,540 --> 00:10:18,340
free lawyer from a great speech,

278
00:10:18,340 --> 00:10:21,560
or a famous senator, or a crowd in

279
00:10:21,560 --> 00:10:22,040
the street.

280
00:10:22,880 --> 00:10:24,940
We got it because one poor,

281
00:10:24,940 --> 00:10:28,560
twice-doubted prisoner refused to accept

282
00:10:28,560 --> 00:10:30,880
that justice was something only people with

283
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:31,805
money could buy —

284
00:10:32,500 --> 00:10:34,440
and because he wrote it down and mailed

285
00:10:34,440 --> 00:10:35,120
it in.

286
00:10:35,940 --> 00:10:38,160
Clarence Earl Gideon got the ending you

287
00:10:38,160 --> 00:10:39,180
almost never get.

288
00:10:39,780 --> 00:10:42,800
He won at the highest court in the

289
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:45,540
land, and then he won his freedom too.

290
00:10:45,540 --> 00:10:49,120
But the thing he really won was never

291
00:10:49,120 --> 00:10:50,320
just for him.

292
00:10:50,320 --> 00:10:50,920
He won a rule —

293
00:10:52,300 --> 00:10:53,620
that in an American courtroom,

294
00:10:53,620 --> 00:10:55,860
you do not have to face the full

295
00:10:55,860 --> 00:10:56,729
weight of the state with an empty chair

296
00:10:56,762 --> 00:10:57,395
beside you.

297
00:10:57,396 --> 00:10:59,740
That is the hidden system behind a phrase

298
00:10:59,740 --> 00:11:01,220
you have heard a hundred times.

299
00:11:01,860 --> 00:11:04,100
"You have the right to an attorney" is

300
00:11:04,100 --> 00:11:05,200
not set dressing.

301
00:11:05,780 --> 00:11:07,940
It is a promise paid for by a

302
00:11:07,940 --> 00:11:12,610
prisoner with a pencil —

303
00:11:12,611 --> 00:11:14,100
powerful, real, and still, to this day,

304
00:11:14,100 --> 00:11:15,000
unfinished.

305
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:18,800
Next time, we open the door on who

306
00:11:18,800 --> 00:11:20,900
decides what counts as a crime in the

307
00:11:20,900 --> 00:11:21,620
first place.

308
00:11:22,220 --> 00:11:25,460
Until then: now you know who actually gets

309
00:11:25,460 --> 00:11:27,211
a lawyer —

310
00:11:27,212 --> 00:11:27,300
and why.
